 ATHENS, Dec 6 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Greek coastguard rescued about 200 illegal immigrants on Thursday from a ship wallowing in heavy seas south of the island of Crete, authorities said. One man was found dead, possibly from an illness, and more than 190 others, including many children, were taken off the cargo vessel and transferred to Crete. "At this moment, they have disembarked. In total there are 193 people plus seven crew members. One person was found dead," said a Merchant Marine Ministry official, who declined to be named. The 120-metre (394-foot) ship sent an emergency signal and floundered in rough seas for hours before it was spotted by rescue helicopters and towed close to the island. The immigrants were mostly from Egypt. Thousands of economic migrants try every year to reach Europe by crossing Greece's sea and land borders illegally from Asia or Africa, often perishing in the attem
